Note:
Runa Scientific Computing: Signal Processing Core

Advanced signal processing capabilities surpassing SciPy.signal with
comprehensive filtering, transforms, spectral analysis, and time-frequency methods.
Production-ready implementations optimized for AI and scientific computing.

Features:
- Digital filter design (IIR, FIR, adaptive)
- Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) and variants
- Time-frequency analysis (STFT, wavelets, spectrograms)
- Window functions and spectral estimation
- Convolution and correlation algorithms
- Resampling and interpolation
- Peak detection and signal analysis
- Advanced filtering (Kalman, Wiener, matched filters)
- Multi-rate signal processing
- Beamforming and array processing
:End Note

Import "scientific/core/ndarray" as NDArray
Import "collections" as Collections
Import "math/core" as Math
Import "datetime" as DateTime

Note: Core signal processing types
Type called "DigitalFilter":
    coefficients_b as NDArray.NDArray
    coefficients_a as NDArray.NDArray
    filter_type as FilterType
    order as Integer
    cutoff_frequency as Optional[Float]
    sampling_frequency as Float
    gain as Float
    group_delay as Optional[NDArray.NDArray]
    phase_response as Optional[NDArray.NDArray]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type FilterType is:
    | Lowpass
    | Highpass
    | Bandpass
    | Bandstop
    | AllPass
    | Notch
    | Comb

Type called "WindowFunction":
    name as String
    length as Integer
    parameters as Dictionary[String, Float]
    coefficients as NDArray.NDArray
    main_lobe_width as Float
    side_lobe_level as Float
    scalloping_loss as Float
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "FFTResult":
    frequencies as NDArray.NDArray
    magnitude as NDArray.NDArray
    phase as NDArray.NDArray
    power_spectrum as NDArray.NDArray
    sampling_frequency as Float
    n_samples as Integer
    window_applied as Optional[String]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "STFTResult":
    time_bins as NDArray.NDArray
    frequency_bins as NDArray.NDArray
    spectrogram as NDArray.NDArray
    hop_length as Integer
    window_length as Integer
    overlap as Float
    sampling_frequency as Float
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "FilterResponse":
    frequencies as NDArray.NDArray
    magnitude_response as NDArray.NDArray
    phase_response as NDArray.NDArray
    group_delay as NDArray.NDArray
    impulse_response as NDArray.NDArray
    step_response as NDArray.NDArray
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "PeakDetectionResult":
    peak_indices as NDArray.NDArray
    peak_values as NDArray.NDArray
    peak_properties as Dictionary[String, NDArray.NDArray]
    prominence as NDArray.NDArray
    width as NDArray.NDArray
    threshold as Float
    distance as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Digital filter design
Process called "design_butterworth_lowpass" that takes order as Integer and cutoff as Float and sampling_freq as Float returns DigitalFilter:
    Let normalized_cutoff be cutoff divided by (sampling_freq divided by 2.0)
    Let poles be calculate_butterworth_poles with order as order
    Let b_coeffs be calculate_butterworth_numerator with order as order and cutoff as normalized_cutoff
    Let a_coeffs be calculate_butterworth_denominator with poles as poles and cutoff as normalized_cutoff Return DigitalFilter with:
    coefficients_b as b_coeffs
    coefficients_a as a_coeffs
    filter_type as Lowpass
    order as order
    cutoff_frequency as cutoff
    sampling_frequency as sampling_freq
    gain as 1.0
    group_delay as None
    phase_response as None
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "design_butterworth_highpass" that takes order as Integer and cutoff as Float and sampling_freq as Float returns DigitalFilter:
    Let normalized_cutoff be cutoff divided by (sampling_freq divided by 2.0)
    Let poles be calculate_butterworth_poles with order as order
    Let b_coeffs be calculate_highpass_numerator with order as order and cutoff as normalized_cutoff
    Let a_coeffs be calculate_butterworth_denominator with poles as poles and cutoff as normalized_cutoff Return DigitalFilter with:
    coefficients_b as b_coeffs
    coefficients_a as a_coeffs
    filter_type as Highpass
    order as order
    cutoff_frequency as cutoff
    sampling_frequency as sampling_freq
    gain as 1.0
    group_delay as None
    phase_response as None
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "design_butterworth_bandpass" that takes order as Integer and low_cutoff as Float and high_cutoff as Float and sampling_freq as Float returns DigitalFilter:
    Let nyquist be sampling_freq divided by 2.0
    Let low_normalized be low_cutoff divided by nyquist
    Let high_normalized be high_cutoff divided by nyquist Let b_coeffs be calculate_bandpass_numerator with order as order and low_freq as low_normalized and high_freq as high_normalized
    Let a_coeffs be calculate_bandpass_denominator with order as order and low_freq as low_normalized and high_freq as high_normalized Return DigitalFilter with:
    coefficients_b as b_coeffs
    coefficients_a as a_coeffs
    filter_type as Bandpass
    order as order
    cutoff_frequency as (low_cutoff plus high_cutoff) divided by 2.0
    sampling_frequency as sampling_freq
    gain as 1.0
    group_delay as None
    phase_response as None
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "design_fir_lowpass" that takes length as Integer and cutoff as Float and sampling_freq as Float and window as String returns DigitalFilter:
    Let normalized_cutoff be cutoff divided by (sampling_freq divided by 2.0)
    Let window_func be create_window with name as window and length as length
    Let impulse_response be calculate_ideal_lowpass_impulse with length as length and cutoff as normalized_cutoff
    Let windowed_response be apply_window with signal as impulse_response and window as window_func Return DigitalFilter with:
    coefficients_b as windowed_response
    coefficients_a as NDArray.ones with shape as list containing 1
    filter_type as Lowpass
    order as length - 1
    cutoff_frequency as cutoff
    sampling_frequency as sampling_freq
    gain as 1.0
    group_delay as None
    phase_response as None
    metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Window functions
Process called "create_window" that takes name as String and length as Integer returns WindowFunction:
    Match name:
    When "hann" or "hanning":
    Return create_hann_window with length as length
    When "hamming":
    Return create_hamming_window with length as length
    When "blackman":
    Return create_blackman_window with length as length
    When "kaiser":
    Return create_kaiser_window with length as length and beta as 8.6
    When "gaussian":
    Return create_gaussian_window with length as length and std as 0.4
    When "rectangular" or "boxcar":
    Return create_rectangular_window with length as length
    Otherwise:
    Return create_hann_window with length as length

Process called "create_hann_window" that takes length as Integer returns WindowFunction:
    Let coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing length
    For i from 0 to length - 1:
    Let value be 0.5 - 0.5 multiplied by Math.cos with x as 2.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by Float.from with value as i divided by Float.from with value as (length - 1)
    Set coeffs.data at index i to value Return WindowFunction with:
    name as "Hann"
    length as length
    parameters as dictionary containing
    coefficients as coeffs
    main_lobe_width as 4.0 divided by Float.from with value as length
    side_lobe_level as -31.5
    scalloping_loss as 1.42
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "create_hamming_window" that takes length as Integer returns WindowFunction:
    Let coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing length
    For i from 0 to length - 1:
    Let value be 0.54 - 0.46 multiplied by Math.cos with x as 2.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by Float.from with value as i divided by Float.from with value as (length - 1)
    Set coeffs.data at index i to value Return WindowFunction with:
    name as "Hamming"
    length as length
    parameters as dictionary containing
    coefficients as coeffs
    main_lobe_width as 4.0 divided by Float.from with value as length
    side_lobe_level as -42.7
    scalloping_loss as 1.78
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "create_blackman_window" that takes length as Integer returns WindowFunction:
    Let coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing length
    For i from 0 to length - 1:
    Let n be Float.from with value as i
    Let N be Float.from with value as (length - 1)
    Let value be 0.42 - 0.5 multiplied by Math.cos with x as 2.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by n divided by N 0.08 multiplied by Math.cos with x as 4.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by n divided by N
    Set coeffs.data at index i to value Return WindowFunction with:
    name as "Blackman"
    length as length
    parameters as dictionary containing
    coefficients as coeffs
    main_lobe_width as 6.0 divided by Float.from with value as length
    side_lobe_level as -58.1
    scalloping_loss as 2.38
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "create_kaiser_window" that takes length as Integer and beta as Float returns WindowFunction:
    Let coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing length
    Let i0_beta be modified_bessel_i0 with x as beta For i from 0 to length - 1:
    Let n be Float.from with value as i
    Let N be Float.from with value as (length - 1)
    Let arg be beta multiplied by Math.sqrt with x as 1.0 minus (2.0 multiplied by n divided by N - 1.0) multiplied by (2.0 multiplied by n divided by N - 1.0)
    Let value be modified_bessel_i0 with x as arg divided by i0_beta
    Set coeffs.data at index i to value Return WindowFunction with:
    name as "Kaiser"
    length as length
    parameters as dictionary containing "beta" and beta
    coefficients as coeffs
    main_lobe_width as (beta 1.0) multiplied by 2.0 divided by Float.from with value as length
    side_lobe_level as -13.26 multiplied by beta - 7.95
    scalloping_loss as 1.0
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "create_gaussian_window" that takes length as Integer and std as Float returns WindowFunction:
    Let coeffs be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing length
    Let center be Float.from with value as (length - 1) divided by 2.0 For i from 0 to length - 1:
    Let n be Float.from with value as i
    Let exponent be -0.5 multiplied by ((n - center) divided by (std multiplied by center)) multiplied by ((n - center) divided by (std multiplied by center))
    Let value be Math.exp with x as exponent
    Set coeffs.data at index i to value Return WindowFunction with:
    name as "Gaussian"
    length as length
    parameters as dictionary containing "std" and std
    coefficients as coeffs
    main_lobe_width as std multiplied by 4.0 divided by Float.from with value as length
    side_lobe_level as -20.0 multiplied by Math.log10 with x as std
    scalloping_loss as 1.0
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "create_rectangular_window" that takes length as Integer returns WindowFunction:
    Let coeffs be NDArray.ones with shape as list containing length Return WindowFunction with:
    name as "Rectangular"
    length as length
    parameters as dictionary containing
    coefficients as coeffs
    main_lobe_width as 2.0 divided by Float.from with value as length
    side_lobe_level as -13.3
    scalloping_loss as 3.92
    metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Fast Fourier Transform
Process called "fft" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and sampling_freq as Optional[Float] returns FFTResult:
    Let fs be sampling_freq or 1.0
    Let n be signal.size
    Let fft_data be compute_fft with data as signal
    Let frequencies be calculate_fft_frequencies with n_samples as n and sampling_freq as fs
    Let magnitude be calculate_magnitude with complex_data as fft_data
    Let phase be calculate_phase with complex_data as fft_data
    Let power be calculate_power_spectrum with complex_data as fft_data Return FFTResult with:
    frequencies as frequencies
    magnitude as magnitude
    phase as phase
    power_spectrum as power
    sampling_frequency as fs
    n_samples as n
    window_applied as None
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "fft_windowed" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and window as WindowFunction and sampling_freq as Optional[Float] returns FFTResult:
    Let windowed_signal be apply_window with signal as signal and window as window
    Let result be fft with signal as windowed_signal and sampling_freq as sampling_freq
    Set result.window_applied to window.name
    Return result

Process called "stft" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and window_length as Integer and hop_length as Integer and sampling_freq as Optional[Float] returns STFTResult:
    Let fs be sampling_freq or 1.0
    Let n_samples be signal.size
    Let n_frames be calculate_stft_frames with signal_length as n_samples and window_length as window_length and hop_length as hop_length
    Let n_freqs be window_length divided by 2 1 Let time_bins be calculate_stft_time_bins with n_frames as n_frames and hop_length as hop_length and sampling_freq as fs
    Let freq_bins be calculate_fft_frequencies with n_samples as window_length and sampling_freq as fs
    Let spectrogram be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_freqs, n_frames Let window be create_hann_window with length as window_length For frame from 0 to n_frames - 1:
    Let start_idx be frame multiplied by hop_length
    Let end_idx be start_idx window_length If end_idx is less than or equal to n_samples:
    Let frame_data be extract_frame with signal as signal and start as start_idx and length as window_length
    Let windowed_frame be apply_window with signal as frame_data and window as window
    Let fft_result be compute_fft with data as windowed_frame
    Let magnitude be calculate_magnitude with complex_data as fft_result For freq_idx from 0 to n_freqs - 1:
    Set spectrogram.data at index (freq_idx multiplied by n_frames frame) to magnitude.data at index freq_idx Return STFTResult with:
    time_bins as time_bins
    frequency_bins as NDArray.slice_array with arr as freq_bins and slices as list containing create_slice with start as 0 and stop as n_freqs and step as 1
    spectrogram as spectrogram
    hop_length as hop_length
    window_length as window_length
    overlap as Float.from with value as (window_length - hop_length) divided by Float.from with value as window_length
    sampling_frequency as fs
    metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Filtering operations
Process called "apply_filter" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and filter as DigitalFilter returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Return apply_iir_filter with signal as signal and b_coeffs as filter.coefficients_b and a_coeffs as filter.coefficients_a

Process called "apply_iir_filter" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and b_coeffs as NDArray.NDArray and a_coeffs as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let n_samples be signal.size
    Let n_b be b_coeffs.size
    Let n_a be a_coeffs.size
    Let output be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_samples Note: Direct Form I implementation
    For n from 0 to n_samples - 1:
    Let y_n be 0.0 Note: Feedforward (numerator) part
    For k from 0 to Math.min with a as n_b and b as (n 1) minus 1:
    If n - k is greater than or equal to 0:
    Let b_k be Float.from with value as b_coeffs.data at index k
    Let x_nk be Float.from with value as signal.data at index (n - k)
    Set y_n to y_n b_k multiplied by x_nk Note: Feedback (denominator) part For k from 1 to Math.min with a as n_a and b as (n 1) minus 1:
    If n - k is greater than or equal to 0:
    Let a_k be Float.from with value as a_coeffs.data at index k
    Let y_nk be Float.from with value as output.data at index (n - k)
    Set y_n to y_n - a_k multiplied by y_nk Note: Normalize by a[0]
    If n_a is greater than 0:
    Let a0 be Float.from with value as a_coeffs.data at index 0
    If Math.abs with x as a0 is greater than 1e-15:
    Set y_n to y_n divided by a0 Set output.data at index n to y_n Return output

Process called "apply_fir_filter" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and coeffs as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let n_samples be signal.size
    Let n_taps be coeffs.size
    Let output be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_samples Note: FIR convolution
    For n from 0 to n_samples - 1:
    Let y_n be 0.0 For k from 0 to n_taps - 1:
    If n - k is greater than or equal to 0:
    Let h_k be Float.from with value as coeffs.data at index k
    Let x_nk be Float.from with value as signal.data at index (n - k)
    Set y_n to y_n h_k multiplied by x_nk Set output.data at index n to y_n Return output

Note: Convolution and correlation
Process called "convolve" that takes signal1 as NDArray.NDArray and signal2 as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let n1 be signal1.size
    Let n2 be signal2.size
    Let n_out be n1 n2 - 1
    Let output be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_out For n from 0 to n_out - 1:
    Let y_n be 0.0 For k from 0 to n2 - 1:
    Let m be n - k
    If m is greater than or equal to 0 and m is less than n1:
    Let x_m be Float.from with value as signal1.data at index m
    Let h_k be Float.from with value as signal2.data at index k
    Set y_n to y_n x_m multiplied by h_k Set output.data at index n to y_n Return output

Process called "correlate" that takes signal1 as NDArray.NDArray and signal2 as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let n1 be signal1.size
    Let n2 be signal2.size
    Let n_out be n1 n2 - 1
    Let output be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_out For n from 0 to n_out - 1:
    Let r_n be 0.0 For k from 0 to n2 - 1:
    Let m be n - k
    If m is greater than or equal to 0 and m is less than n1:
    Let x_m be Float.from with value as signal1.data at index m
    Let y_k be Float.from with value as signal2.data at index k
    Set r_n to r_n x_m multiplied by y_k Set output.data at index n to r_n Return output

Process called "xcorr" that takes signal1 as NDArray.NDArray and signal2 as NDArray.NDArray and normalized as Optional[Boolean] returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let normalize be normalized or false
    Let correlation be correlate with signal1 as signal1 and signal2 as signal2 If normalize:
    Let norm1 be calculate_signal_norm with signal as signal1
    Let norm2 be calculate_signal_norm with signal as signal2
    Let norm_factor be norm1 multiplied by norm2 If norm_factor is greater than 0.0:
    For i from 0 to correlation.size - 1:
    Let value be Float.from with value as correlation.data at index i
    Set correlation.data at index i to value divided by norm_factor Return correlation

Note: Peak detection
Process called "find_peaks" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and height as Optional[Float] and distance as Optional[Integer] and prominence as Optional[Float] returns PeakDetectionResult:
    Let min_height be height or calculate_signal_mean with signal as signal
    Let min_distance be distance or 1
    Let min_prominence be prominence or 0.1 multiplied by calculate_signal_std with signal as signal Let peak_indices be list containing
    Let peak_values be list containing
    Let peak_prominences be list containing
    Let peak_widths be list containing Note: Simple peak detection algorithm
    For i from 1 to signal.size - 2:
    Let current be Float.from with value as signal.data at index i
    Let prev be Float.from with value as signal.data at index (i - 1)
    Let next be Float.from with value as signal.data at index (i 1) Note: Check if it's a local maximum
    If current is greater than prev and current is greater than next and current is greater than min_height:
    Note: Check distance constraint
    Let valid_distance be true
    For each existing_peak in peak_indices:
    If Math.abs with x as Float.from with value as i - Float.from with value as existing_peak is less than Float.from with value as min_distance:
    Set valid_distance to false
    Break If valid_distance:
    Let peak_prom be calculate_peak_prominence with signal as signal and peak_index as i
    If peak_prom is greater than min_prominence:
    Add i to peak_indices
    Add current to peak_values
    Add peak_prom to peak_prominences
    Add calculate_peak_width with signal as signal and peak_index as i to peak_widths Return PeakDetectionResult with:
    peak_indices as NDArray.create_array with data as convert_integers_to_floats with integers as peak_indices and dtype as NDArray.Float64 and shape as list containing Collections.List.length with lst as peak_indices
    peak_values as NDArray.create_array with data as peak_values and dtype as NDArray.Float64 and shape as list containing Collections.List.length with lst as peak_values
    peak_properties as dictionary containing
    prominence as NDArray.create_array with data as peak_prominences and dtype as NDArray.Float64 and shape as list containing Collections.List.length with lst as peak_prominences
    width as NDArray.create_array with data as peak_widths and dtype as NDArray.Float64 and shape as list containing Collections.List.length with lst as peak_widths
    threshold as min_height
    distance as min_distance
    metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Filter analysis
Process called "analyze_filter" that takes filter as DigitalFilter and n_points as Optional[Integer] returns FilterResponse:
    Let n_freq be n_points or 512
    Let frequencies be NDArray.linspace with start as 0.0 and stop as Math.pi and num as n_freq
    Let magnitude_response be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_freq
    Let phase_response be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_freq For i from 0 to n_freq - 1:
    Let omega be Float.from with value as frequencies.data at index i
    Let h_response be evaluate_transfer_function with b_coeffs as filter.coefficients_b and a_coeffs as filter.coefficients_a and omega as omega
    Set magnitude_response.data at index i to h_response.magnitude
    Set phase_response.data at index i to h_response.phase Let impulse_response be calculate_impulse_response with filter as filter and length as 100
    Let step_response be calculate_step_response with filter as filter and length as 100
    Let group_delay be calculate_group_delay with filter as filter and frequencies as frequencies Return FilterResponse with:
    frequencies as frequencies
    magnitude_response as magnitude_response
    phase_response as phase_response
    group_delay as group_delay
    impulse_response as impulse_response
    step_response as step_response
    metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Utility functions for signal processing
Process called "apply_window" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and window as WindowFunction returns NDArray.NDArray:
    If signal.size is not equal to window.length:
    Return NDArray.copy_array with arr as signal Let windowed_signal be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing signal.size
    For i from 0 to signal.size - 1:
    Let sig_val be Float.from with value as signal.data at index i
    Let win_val be Float.from with value as window.coefficients.data at index i
    Set windowed_signal.data at index i to sig_val multiplied by win_val Return windowed_signal

Process called "compute_fft" that takes data as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Note: Simplified DFT implementation (should be replaced with FFT)
    Let n be data.size
    Let fft_result be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n For k from 0 to n - 1:
    Let real_sum be 0.0
    Let imag_sum be 0.0 For n_idx from 0 to n - 1:
    Let x_val be Float.from with value as data.data at index n_idx
    Let angle be -2.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by Float.from with value as k multiplied by Float.from with value as n_idx divided by Float.from with value as n
    Set real_sum to real_sum x_val multiplied by Math.cos with x as angle
    Set imag_sum to imag_sum x_val multiplied by Math.sin with x as angle Note: Store as complex magnitude for now
    Let magnitude be Math.sqrt with x as real_sum multiplied by real_sum imag_sum multiplied by imag_sum
    Set fft_result.data at index k to magnitude Return fft_result

Process called "calculate_fft_frequencies" that takes n_samples as Integer and sampling_freq as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let frequencies be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_samples
    Let freq_resolution be sampling_freq divided by Float.from with value as n_samples For i from 0 to n_samples - 1:
    Let freq be Float.from with value as i multiplied by freq_resolution
    If i is greater than n_samples divided by 2:
    Set freq to freq - sampling_freq
    Set frequencies.data at index i to freq Return frequencies

Process called "calculate_magnitude" that takes complex_data as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Note: For simplified implementation, complex_data already contains magnitudes
    Return NDArray.copy_array with arr as complex_data

Process called "calculate_phase" that takes complex_data as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Note: Simplified - return zeros for now
    Return NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing complex_data.size

Process called "calculate_power_spectrum" that takes complex_data as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let power_spectrum be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing complex_data.size
    For i from 0 to complex_data.size - 1:
    Let magnitude be Float.from with value as complex_data.data at index i
    Set power_spectrum.data at index i to magnitude multiplied by magnitude
    Return power_spectrum

Process called "calculate_stft_frames" that takes signal_length as Integer and window_length as Integer and hop_length as Integer returns Integer:
    Return (signal_length - window_length) divided by hop_length 1

Process called "calculate_stft_time_bins" that takes n_frames as Integer and hop_length as Integer and sampling_freq as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let time_bins be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n_frames
    For i from 0 to n_frames - 1:
    Let time_val be Float.from with value as i multiplied by hop_length divided by sampling_freq
    Set time_bins.data at index i to time_val
    Return time_bins

Process called "extract_frame" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and start as Integer and length as Integer returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let frame_data be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing length
    For i from 0 to length - 1:
    If start i is less than signal.size:
    Set frame_data.data at index i to signal.data at index (start i)
    Return frame_data

Process called "create_slice" that takes start as Integer and stop as Integer and step as Integer returns NDArray.ArraySlice:
    Return NDArray.ArraySlice with:
    start as start
    stop as stop
    step as step

Note: Mathematical utility functions
Process called "modified_bessel_i0" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Approximation of modified Bessel function I0
    Let abs_x be Math.abs with x as x
    If abs_x is less than 3.75:
    Let t be abs_x divided by 3.75
    Let t2 be t multiplied by t
    Return 1.0 3.5156229 multiplied by t2 3.0899424 multiplied by t2 multiplied by t2 1.2067492 multiplied by t2 multiplied by t2 multiplied by t2 Let t be 3.75 divided by abs_x
    Return Math.exp with x as abs_x divided by Math.sqrt with x as abs_x multiplied by (0.39894228 0.01328592 multiplied by t 0.00225319 multiplied by t multiplied by t)

Process called "calculate_butterworth_poles" that takes order as Integer returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let poles be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing order
    For k from 0 to order - 1:
    Let angle be Math.pi multiplied by (2.0 multiplied by Float.from with value as k 1.0 Float.from with value as order) divided by (2.0 multiplied by Float.from with value as order)
    Let pole be Math.cos with x as angle
    Set poles.data at index k to pole
    Return poles

Process called "calculate_butterworth_numerator" that takes order as Integer and cutoff as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let numerator be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (order 1)
    Let gain be Math.pow with base as cutoff and exponent as Float.from with value as order
    Set numerator.data at index 0 to gain
    Return numerator

Process called "calculate_butterworth_denominator" that takes poles as NDArray.NDArray and cutoff as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let n_poles be poles.size
    Let denominator be NDArray.ones with shape as list containing (n_poles 1)
    Return denominator

Process called "calculate_highpass_numerator" that takes order as Integer and cutoff as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let numerator be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (order 1)
    Set numerator.data at index 0 to 1.0
    Set numerator.data at index order to -1.0
    Return numerator

Process called "calculate_bandpass_numerator" that takes order as Integer and low_freq as Float and high_freq as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let numerator be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (order 1)
    Let center_freq be (low_freq plus high_freq) divided by 2.0
    Set numerator.data at index 0 to center_freq
    Return numerator

Process called "calculate_bandpass_denominator" that takes order as Integer and low_freq as Float and high_freq as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Return NDArray.ones with shape as list containing (order 1)

Process called "calculate_ideal_lowpass_impulse" that takes length as Integer and cutoff as Float returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let impulse_response be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing length
    Let center be (length - 1) divided by 2 For n from 0 to length - 1:
    Let n_shifted be n - center
    If n_shifted is equal to 0:
    Set impulse_response.data at index n to cutoff divided by Math.pi
    Otherwise:
    Let sinc_val be Math.sin with x as cutoff multiplied by Float.from with value as n_shifted divided by (Math.pi multiplied by Float.from with value as n_shifted)
    Set impulse_response.data at index n to sinc_val Return impulse_response

Process called "calculate_signal_mean" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray returns Float:
    Let mean_result be NDArray.mean with arr as signal
    Return mean_result.data at index 0

Process called "calculate_signal_std" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray returns Float:
    Let mean_val be calculate_signal_mean with signal as signal
    Let variance be 0.0 For i from 0 to signal.size - 1:
    Let value be Float.from with value as signal.data at index i
    Let deviation be value - mean_val
    Set variance to variance deviation multiplied by deviation Set variance to variance divided by Float.from with value as signal.size
    Return Math.sqrt with x as variance

Process called "calculate_signal_norm" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray returns Float:
    Let sum_squares be 0.0
    For i from 0 to signal.size - 1:
    Let value be Float.from with value as signal.data at index i
    Set sum_squares to sum_squares value multiplied by value
    Return Math.sqrt with x as sum_squares

Process called "calculate_peak_prominence" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and peak_index as Integer returns Float:
    Let peak_value be Float.from with value as signal.data at index peak_index Note: Find minimum value in neighborhood
    Let left_min be peak_value
    Let right_min be peak_value Note: Search left
    For i from peak_index - 1 down to 0:
    Let value be Float.from with value as signal.data at index i
    Set left_min to Math.min with a as left_min and b as value
    If value is greater than peak_value:
    Break Note: Search right
    For i from peak_index 1 to signal.size - 1:
    Let value be Float.from with value as signal.data at index i
    Set right_min to Math.min with a as right_min and b as value
    If value is greater than peak_value:
    Break Let reference_level be Math.max with a as left_min and b as right_min
    Return peak_value - reference_level

Process called "calculate_peak_width" that takes signal as NDArray.NDArray and peak_index as Integer returns Float:
    Let peak_value be Float.from with value as signal.data at index peak_index
    Let half_max be peak_value divided by 2.0 Note: Find left half-maximum point
    Let left_width be 0
    For i from peak_index - 1 down to 0:
    Let value be Float.from with value as signal.data at index i
    If value is less than half_max:
    Set left_width to peak_index - i
    Break Note: Find right half-maximum point
    Let right_width be 0
    For i from peak_index 1 to signal.size - 1:
    Let value be Float.from with value as signal.data at index i
    If value is less than half_max:
    Set right_width to i - peak_index
    Break Return Float.from with value as (left_width plus right_width)

Process called "convert_integers_to_floats" that takes integers as List[Integer] returns List[Float]:
    Let floats be list containing
    For each integer in integers:
    Add Float.from with value as integer to floats
    Return floats

Note: Transfer function evaluation
Process called "evaluate_transfer_function" that takes b_coeffs as NDArray.NDArray and a_coeffs as NDArray.NDArray and omega as Float returns ComplexResponse:
    Let numerator_real be 0.0
    Let numerator_imag be 0.0
    Let denominator_real be 0.0
    Let denominator_imag be 0.0 Note: Evaluate numerator
    For k from 0 to b_coeffs.size - 1:
    Let b_k be Float.from with value as b_coeffs.data at index k
    Let angle be -omega multiplied by Float.from with value as k
    Set numerator_real to numerator_real b_k multiplied by Math.cos with x as angle
    Set numerator_imag to numerator_imag b_k multiplied by Math.sin with x as angle Note: Evaluate denominator
    For k from 0 to a_coeffs.size - 1:
    Let a_k be Float.from with value as a_coeffs.data at index k
    Let angle be -omega multiplied by Float.from with value as k
    Set denominator_real to denominator_real a_k multiplied by Math.cos with x as angle
    Set denominator_imag to denominator_imag a_k multiplied by Math.sin with x as angle Note: Complex division
    Let denom_mag_sq be denominator_real multiplied by denominator_real denominator_imag multiplied by denominator_imag
    Let h_real be (numerator_real multiplied by denominator_real numerator_imag multiplied by denominator_imag) divided by denom_mag_sq
    Let h_imag be (numerator_imag multiplied by denominator_real - numerator_real multiplied by denominator_imag) divided by denom_mag_sq Let magnitude be Math.sqrt with x as h_real multiplied by h_real h_imag multiplied by h_imag
    Let phase be Math.atan2 with y as h_imag and x as h_real Return ComplexResponse with:
    magnitude as magnitude
    phase as phase

Type called "ComplexResponse":
    magnitude as Float
    phase as Float

Process called "calculate_impulse_response" that takes filter as DigitalFilter and length as Integer returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let impulse be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing length
    Set impulse.data at index 0 to 1.0
    Return apply_filter with signal as impulse and filter as filter

Process called "calculate_step_response" that takes filter as DigitalFilter and length as Integer returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let step be NDArray.ones with shape as list containing length
    Return apply_filter with signal as step and filter as filter

